18/18

Overall, I just hope people eventually realize that when we create a world in which the most marginalized members of society can feel protected that EVERYBODY wins.

Thanks for reading.

17/18

Do better. 

Everyone.

And men, being a REAL MAN means not being afraid to call out other men for being harmful and abusive towards a woman for simply EXISTING IN HER OWN BODY.

Hold each other accountable.

16/18

ALL women and femmes, even and ESPECIALLY the non-white and/or larger-bodied ones who don't look like you or who you aren't attracted to, deserve protection.

ALL.

15/18

There’s a whole lotta “Protect Black Women” rhetoric online, but I don’t often see it in action. We deserve the same level care, consideration, and tenderness as our white counterparts. 

It’s the BARE minimum.

Why were people afraid to step in when I clearly needed help?

14/18

I’m just here to remind you all that we are historically the most consistently under-protected group in this country and it’s bullshit. 

If stuff like what happened to me is still tolerated in 2022, are we truly doing enough to make ALL women feel safe?

**note 2: FWIW, dear reader, I’m never NOT gonna see the world through a racial or gendered lens bc society is set up so that people like me don’t have the luxury to not think about their race or gender. Especially if/when we’re being mistreated. Don’t blame me blame the system.

13/18

I’m not here to speak on behalf of every Black woman**, especially since women with darker skin than mine and queer Black femmes face challenges I’ll never truly know — which is yet another way the world is failing us, but I digress.

*note: it’s basically saying “Your skin color means you’re built to handle consistent abuse unlike a ‘normal’ human being.”
The strong Black woman trope is dangerous. It enables/emboldens ppl to be doubly awful to us based solely on the idea we can handle it. A lot of us can’t.

12/18

No one came to my defense or my aid in that moment, most likely because, again, they presumed that as a Black woman I’m “strong” enough to take it. 

I’m. Not. Strong.

“Strong” is NOT the compliment you think it is when you say it to a Black woman.*

11/18

Sadly this isn’t my 1st rodeo with a man hurling abuse at me, threatening my life. I was triggered and I have every right to grieve over my situation. I just don’t have the internet clout or enough WWTs to hear “poor baby” about it. ALL victims deserve to hear “poor baby.”

10/18

I’m far less shaken up today. But a man followed me down the street yelling and threatening to kill me in broad daylight because I stood up for myself when he made disgusting, uninvited remarks about my body.

What if he acted on his word? Then what?

9/18

No. I can't. I shouldn't HAVE to be strong. No one should. No Black woman should have to incur abuse simply because of the harmful stereotype that we can "take it."

FUCK that.

8/18

Am I or women who look like me not worthy of that kind of protection?

Or, ya know, "She's a Black woman, they're strong, she can handle it."

7/18

A guy standing by a bike rack who'd seen (and heard) everything go down yelled out "HEY" at the harasser in the white lady's defense.

Where was that energy for me 20 seconds before? Did me & my gigantic backside not deserve a "HEY" from bike-rack guy or anyone else around?

6/18

Again, there were plenty of witnesses to this incident, but no one intervened or said a word.

That is until a white lady walking toward me on my left on the other side of the sidewalk looked at the guy. All she did was look. But the harasser cussed her out, too.

5/18

What some creep thinks of MY body shouldn't have to be MY business, but creepers gonna creep.

I threw up a middle finger at him as I walked off. 
He followed me for a few feet, still screaming, me still with a middle finger in the air.

4/18

As I was walking off he proceeded to further berate me, yelling violent threats. 

Violent threats. Physical harm. To kill me. All because I (nonverbally) admonished him for his nasty remarks about MY body.

3/18

No, sir, I had no idea just HOW gargantuan my ass is, but thanks for going out of your way to inform.

I normally ignore street harassers but as a way of standing up for myself, I made a disgusted face at him from under my mask.

2/18

Thursday evening I was walking to a yoga class wearing yoga clothes—as you do–fully covered, mind you, no actual skin showing, when a man, a Black man, proceeded to make really horrible and disgusting remarks about my body.

Out loud. In front of a whole bunch of people.

So this definitely isn’t coming out of nowhere. Context.

Thread.

Some of you need to look in the mirror more often. Because, I guarantee, if you sh!t on me for writing this, it says way more about you. 
I mean, whatever.
I’m OK. I’ll be OK.
I hope the actors are OK.
I hope they didn’t hear it.
Truly. They deserve SO much better.

This thread isn't a guilt trip, nor a boo-hoo, nor a woe is me. 
It’s a call to DO BETTER. 
It’s a reminder that YOU, white folks, need to step up.

“If you don’t like it here, then leave!”
Isn’t that what people like him love to tell people like me? 
Why aren’t so-called allies keeping that same energy?
It’s about another instance of white people letting everybody down. He was right there in the aisle. Any of you could’ve turned around and told him to GTFO.

Who’s to say.
But it’s not about Black people and what we would do and how we would react if any of us were in my shoes that night.
We shouldn’t even have to be in that position PERIOD.

I know some Black folks reading this are probably like “You’re weak, I would’ve beat his ass right there the first time he said it!”
Would you? 
In that moment, in front of all those people? 
You'd risk stopping the show and risk this old man being portrayed as the victim?

IF YOU HEARD IT WHY DIDN'T YOU STEP UP? 
WHERE WERE YOU IN THE MOMENT?
WHY DID ALL THE WORK HAVE TO FALL ON **MY** BLACK ASS INSTEAD OF YOU PEOPLE COMING TO COLLECT YOUR OWN???
I’m angry. Can you tell?
I don’t get angry often, but I think this occasion merits ire.

They all go about their business. 
They all leave me to do the work. 
I don’t need your thanks, I don’t need your pity, I — WE — need you to be the ally you claim to be.

“Uh huh, yup, I heard it!”
“It was him, he said it!”
“Yeah, I heard!”
Some folks thank me for what I did. 
Yet they all, save for one woman who was adamant about making sure I felt supported in the moment (shoutout to her), confirm what happened and keep walking.

Though what upsets me almost as much as the fact that he said this word THREE TIMES is the fact that like, TWELVE other white people who were sitting in my section come up to me while I’m speaking to a staff member and the house manager say, “I HEARD IT TOO!”

He and everyone else in the theater—except for the actors, obvi—remain silent.
After the curtain call I find someone and let them know what happened. A tad Karen-y of me? Sure. But management should be notified.

He doesn’t say another word. Until he fumbles his phone 30 minutes later. 
“Blurrgggh I dropped my phone.”
But for the rest of the show, other than some occasional demonstrative huffs and puffs to show his discontent to his partner for putting him through this, he is silent.

But again, as this happened, as he says this word, everyone else in the audience remains stone silent. 
He grumbles the N-word a third time. I turn around, lower my masks and firmly say SHUT THE FUCK UP.
I turn back around.

All people would see is this random Black lady attacking a helpless old man.
I don’t need anyone catching me assaulting this dickhead in 4K. Do you?
I’m not confrontational. I don’t like to stick my neck out because I’ve been heavily burned in the past for doing so. This is hard.
I don’t think a lot of you understand the pressure of knowing YOU are automatically the villain in the situation because of your skin color.

No one else in the audience says a word. Not even his companion (wife, caretaker, idk but F her, she’s an enabler).
A scene goes by, he grumbles some more. Says the word again.
I’m seething. My fists are balled up. But I restrain myself because I would be on camera.

Then a minute later grumbles some more and calls the actors the N-word. 
I, the one Black person in my section, turn around and GLARE at him for 10 seconds. GLARE. He goes quiet.
I glare at the white lady sitting to my left 'cuz hey, come get your people. Then I turn back around.

Here’s what I’m really here to discuss.
Within two minutes of the start of the show, this crotchety old (yes, old as in elderly) white man sitting directly behind me starts medium-volume grumbling “flbhghbgb I don’t like this,” “this sucks.” Literally TWO MINUTES into the show.

The theater notified me earlier in the evening that I would be moved from my original section to the stage and that attending the show means I consent to being on camera. Cool, lucky me! I’d be masked up anyway so nbd.
Idk if it was to stream or for posterity’s sake, but two cameramen flanked each side of the staged audience, and cameras were all around the house. We live in the ~*future*~.

What’s interesting about how they staged this performance is that a large portion of the audience would be seated ON THE STAGE. 
It’s essentially theatre in the round. Pretty cool.
They were also recording the show.

I recently got to see a very beautifully executed stage adaptation of the novel “The Bluest Eye.” I highly recommend both the book and the play. It’ll F you up, but what hasn’t already wrecked you to some degree as of 2022?
I digress.

He looks down again and sees the ring on my left finger. He looks back up at me, then his whole head sinks in defeat. He hands me my cart then walks off to retrieve his. We never see each other in the store again.

He looks down to see a pint of oat milk ice cream which is clearly not for his lactose-tolerant ass and realizes his error. He swiftly looks back up at me; our eyes meet again. He apologizes profusely, I reassure him it’s OK. We laugh.

I loop around to the other side of the next aisle — there he is! But he’s turned around and walking off. So I light-jog and tap him on his shoulder. He’s startled. He turns around, and our eyes meet from behind our masks. I say “You have my cart.”

I haven’t been ME at all lately so here’s to getting back to Tooky! 🥂

So, where do I start? Ass-backwards, of course. I was born that way. No, seriously, I came out feet first with the cord around my neck because the late 80s were a reckless time for OBGYNs. I’m an only child for a reason.

Jokes aside, I’m gonna ease into my healing with Step 5.

Side note: never judge someone who hasn’t combed their hair or brushed their teeth. You don’t know what people are going through, and sometimes grooming is one of those things that falls to the wayside when you’re depressed. 
You should always shower but some days it’s hard.

Step 5: self-care, self-care, self-care. 

I’m ashy and dehydrated because I just haven’t been present. I haven’t cared about myself the way I should have and it inadvertently extended to those closest to me.

Don’t get me wrong, I bathe dammit. But man, when I’m sad it’s ROUGH.

Step 4: talk to my doctor about medication. Even if it’s short term. I don’t deserve to struggle. No one does. And sometimes you just need some jumper cables to the car battery to give you a much needed wellness jolt, for lack of a better analogy.

Step 1 to bouncing back: return to a happy heart, an internally healthier body, and a clear state of mind.

Step 2: accept what I’ve lost and move forward.

Step 3: live with gratitude and be thankful for what and who I do have. And I’ve got some AMAZING friends in my corner.

As part of my healing process, the healthiest and most productive thing I can do in this very moment is structure my recovery. 

Baby steps. Just 5 of ‘em. But I know they’ll be effective.

I’m resting now, feeling better. 
I almost NEVER cancel gigs but I’ve cleared my calendar because I’m too unwell to perform.

I love the stage, but it made me lose sight of my non-comedy goals. 

I need to love myself and my family more so that I can bring my best to every show.

Bottom line: I lost everything because I lost myself. 

I wasn’t allowing myself to prioritize what mattered outside of work which let pain and lack of communication fester. SO much could’ve easily been resolved like, a year ago.

Main point: Don’t avoid tough conversations.

The goals were always aligned. Some of us just didn’t lay out our individual plans in a way to make sure that was clear.

Some of us felt like something was missing while others didn’t. Was it them or was it you? Did you really talk enough?

Some of this could’ve been prevented.

Some of us didn’t win the karmic lottery in love.

Some of us tweet too much — especially weird threads like this one. But hey. We all grieve differently.

Some of us need to write open letters to ourselves to process pain.

Some of us need to write more in general. Offline.

Some of us will continue to feel guilty about making the people they care about the most feel like they’ve wasted time. Even when you’ve told them not to.

Some of us didn’t think we were making excuses but fully see how they’d be read as such.

Some of us should’ve drank more (non-sparkling) water.

Some of us didn’t understand why we were always so tired and unmotivated either. Some of us should’ve been more open to taking medication for it.

Some of us don’t want to give up but have to accept when others do.

Some of us miss someone more than they miss us, and we have to be OK with that.

Some of us have to come to terms with the fact that casualties of the pandemic include relationships.

Some of us let decades worth of internalized fat-phobia ruin intimacy.

Some of us have constantly felt behind in life and were only trying to do what they thought they needed to do to feel “caught up” and ready to move forward with their partners. Some of us didn’t realize it came off as selfish.

Some of us were ignoring our mental health, especially after traumatic things like job loss.

Some of us should’ve listened more when loved ones said slow down.

Some of us were ignoring our anger.

Some of us were too angry sometimes and didn’t even know it.

Some of us should’ve gotten more therapy (if we had access to it).

Some of us should’ve been more transparent about the plans they made in their head.

Some of us should’ve been more honest about how much they banked on 2020 and how shaken they were when they lost a year.

Some of us got scared to death of what this pandemic would do to a child and acted too hastily to mitigate that fear.

Some of us operated in fear because they’ve loved before and to love wholly leaves you TOO vulnerable to pain.

Some of us should’ve bought libido enhancers lol.

The goals were always aligned. 

Some of us were just in less of a rush to meet them — especially if they were only recently freed from oppressive homes and finally able to control their own narrative.

Some of us never even got our honeymoon before it was over.

Looking back on 2020-21, the problem was we never truly worked on Us.

The collective.

People never actually sat down and TALK-talked.

We allowed ourselves to be distracted with work and travel and whatever else until lockdown forced us to reevaluate it all.

They say if someone sweeps your feet w/a broom you’ll never get married. Been swept 2x: once in malice once by accident.
They also say if you dream about your fingernails falling off someone will try to hurt you.
High on love; sober on reality.

Anyway, Black is beautiful, anti-Blackness is not. 

If you’re mixed “Looking Black” is just as valid as “looking white” or looking like “so, what ARE you?”

And you don’t have to explain yourself to anyone if you don’t want to.

Pete Wentz was a whole Fall Out Boy but Zendaya, who wore faux locs on a red carpet, was mocked and told she “probably smells like weed and patchouli.”
Halle Berry got a whole new nose to advance her career!
And I bet you didn’t know Yara Shahidi is half Iranian.

Being Black and looking more like your Black parent is not a crime. It doesn’t make you less-than. But anti-Blackness is so pervasive that we elevate ambiguous looking people and flat out erase the Black identity of white-passing people.
Or worse, tell kids to “pick a side.”

I’m not “tell me what you are so I know how to treat you” mixed, I’m “you look Black so I will treat you as such” mixed, and that’s a reality for a lot of people who go home to a parent who looks different than they do. 🤷🏽‍♀️

Biracial doesn’t automatically mean ambiguous looking.
